aim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":4,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":77,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Eltonhead was born in 1378, in Eltonhead, Lancashire, England, his father, John de Eltonhead, was 28 and his mother, Maude de Eltonhead, was 22. He married Mrs. Henry Eltonhead in 1399, in Eltonhead, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1378–":"1378–Surnud","1378–Male":"1378–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1350–1400":"1350–1400","1356–Female":"1356–Surnud","1378":"1378","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1356":"1356","1399":"1399","1376":"1376","1450":"1450","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","after 1400":"